00:00:21.363 --> 00:00:23.280
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: OK,
so let's get started.

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:30.600
I'm just trying
to wire myself up.

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:31.600
OK.

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:39.600
So before we get into
the PowerPoint here.

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:42.620
So basically, what I'm doing is
I'm picking up from the point

00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:47.570
where we left last time,
where we're discussing waves.

00:00:47.570 --> 00:00:53.900
And what I would like to do
now is derive a wave equation

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:58.760
basically, for a
mathematical form

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:02.930
that should allow us to predict
different kinds of waves.

00:01:02.930 --> 00:01:05.459
Of waves, not the waves.

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:08.930
All right, so what
I start with here.

00:01:08.930 --> 00:01:15.060
I start with a general function,
psi, of an argument, eta.

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:24.080
So for those of you who are not
fluent in Greek, this is psi,

00:01:24.080 --> 00:01:25.840
and this is eta.

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:26.340
OK.

00:01:30.850 --> 00:01:32.680
At the moment, these
don't necessarily

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:35.290
have a physical meaning.

00:01:35.290 --> 00:01:39.190
But in order to
produce a wave out

00:01:39.190 --> 00:01:45.310
of this function,
what I can do is

00:01:45.310 --> 00:01:56.640
I can write it as psi,
or f of z comma t,

00:01:56.640 --> 00:02:02.070
equals psi of z minus ct.

00:02:02.070 --> 00:02:05.910
OK, now why is that a wave?

00:02:05.910 --> 00:02:11.220
First of all, z now has
become a spacial coordinate.

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:13.980
t, as usual, is time.

00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:16.650
So if you actually hide time.

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:18.660
So now time is zero.

00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:20.760
Time is a constant or
something like that.

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:24.330
Then you actually have
basically the same argument.

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:27.060
But if you allow
time to increase,

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:30.360
then you can see that
the time increase will

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:35.060
have the effect of
sliding the same shape

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:37.350
along the spatial axis.

00:02:37.350 --> 00:02:43.560
So for example, let's take this
as our reference point here.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:46.440
The first peak after
you advance time

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:50.330
a little further than
this point has moved fast,

00:02:50.330 --> 00:02:51.970
has moved to the right.

00:02:51.970 --> 00:02:55.780
And how much is this distance?

00:02:55.780 --> 00:02:58.440
Well, anybody?

00:02:58.440 --> 00:02:59.700
This is easy.

00:02:59.700 --> 00:03:03.210
I'm just trying to see if the
people in Boston have woken up.

00:03:11.950 --> 00:03:12.450
Yes?

00:03:15.800 --> 00:03:18.020
Nobody's awake in Boston.

00:03:18.020 --> 00:03:20.630
So this distance equals ct.

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:25.910
Because if I set the
argument of this function

00:03:25.910 --> 00:03:29.250
to zero, then basically I
recover my original function.

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:32.510
So basically as I
advance time, the fact

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:35.010
is that this waveform
moves to the right.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:43.770
And at the moment, there's
no obvious motivation

00:03:43.770 --> 00:03:47.620
for why I'm going to do
what I'm about to do.

00:03:47.620 --> 00:03:50.730
But please take my word
for it for a while.

00:03:50.730 --> 00:03:52.620
I'm going to take two
partial derivatives.

00:03:52.620 --> 00:04:01.560
I'm going to take
df dz, and df dt.

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:09.420
OK, df dz equals basically
c prime, where c prime--

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:14.800
I use c prime simply to
denote the derivative of c

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:18.459
with respect to its
mysterious argument.

00:04:18.459 --> 00:04:20.200
So that's very easy.

00:04:20.200 --> 00:04:21.579
What about the affinity?

00:04:31.058 --> 00:04:31.600
That's right.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:33.870
I have to apply the
chain rule, because there

00:04:33.870 --> 00:04:36.390
is a multiplicative
argument inside.

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:42.360
So this is going to be
minus c times c prime.

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:47.880
So because c prime appears
in both places over here,

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:56.460
I can combine these
equations and say, df over dz

00:04:56.460 --> 00:05:02.700
equals minus 1 over c, df dt.

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:07.760
So that is a partial
differential equation.

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:10.720
And you might say, well, what
I did is a bit stupid, right?

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:13.540
Because I had a relatively
simple explanation

00:05:13.540 --> 00:05:14.290
for the wave.

00:05:14.290 --> 00:05:17.110
I actually had the wave
just in front of me.

00:05:17.110 --> 00:05:20.200
And what I did is I wrote a
partial differential equation

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:21.907
which is not very intuitive.

00:05:21.907 --> 00:05:23.740
But the benefit of doing
that is, of course,

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:31.060
that the wave that I wrote here
is a very special, very limited

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:34.420
kind of wave that propagates
without changing shape,

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:36.940
without anything
fancy happening.

00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:39.220
We know from experience,
for example, in real life,

00:05:39.220 --> 00:05:41.780
if you have ever
seen water waves.

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:44.290
Water waves, they
don't quite propagate.

00:05:44.290 --> 00:05:48.700
They change shape in all
kinds of complicated ways.

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:51.820
So even though I
derive this equation

00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:53.355
from that simple shape.

00:05:53.355 --> 00:05:54.730
What we'll see a
little bit later

00:05:54.730 --> 00:05:57.100
that this equation
actually can describe

00:05:57.100 --> 00:05:59.713
much more general waves.

00:05:59.713 --> 00:06:01.630
We're not quite done
yet, because the question

00:06:01.630 --> 00:06:07.940
that I derived here applies
for a wave moving to the right.

00:06:07.940 --> 00:06:10.420
I can equally well
contribute a wave

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:12.150
that is moving to the left.

00:06:12.150 --> 00:06:14.410
And in this case, what
I would have to do

00:06:14.410 --> 00:06:19.890
is I would have to write
f of z comma t equals psi

00:06:19.890 --> 00:06:21.825
or z plus ct.

00:06:21.825 --> 00:06:23.700
A little bit of thought
will convince you now

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:26.280
that if you advance
time, then the wave

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:29.460
will have actually to move to
the left, towards negative z

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:33.170
in order to maintain
its argument.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:36.300
And if I do the same game now.

00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:40.420
Again, I can write
df dz equals c prime.

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:41.790
That did not change.

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:47.160
This time, df dt
equals plus c prime.

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:51.420
Now, I have another partial
differential equation,

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:59.160
df dz equals 1 over c, df dt.

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:01.540
OK, let me put
back the equation.

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:11.200
So this is a wave going
to the left, backwards.

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:17.870
And I had another equation,
df dz equals minus 1

00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:20.790
over c, df dt.

00:07:20.790 --> 00:07:23.210
And that is a way of
going to the right.

00:07:28.230 --> 00:07:29.260
OK.

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:32.980
You can see very easily that
if you take a second derivative

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:35.350
of these equations.

00:07:35.350 --> 00:07:39.000
Let's go back to the first one.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:49.530
If you do the second derivative,
d squared f dz square.

00:07:49.530 --> 00:07:53.140
You will pick up an extra minus
sign from the same equation.

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:57.520
And you will find that it is
1 over c square, d square f,

00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:00.980
dt square.

00:08:00.980 --> 00:08:03.275
You can do the same
in this equation.

00:08:08.530 --> 00:08:10.610
There's no sign
here to begin with.

00:08:10.610 --> 00:08:12.770
But there is one
over here, c square,

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:15.150
d squared f, dt squared.

00:08:15.150 --> 00:08:16.640
So basically, this
single equation.

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:32.530
This single equation can
describe both forward

00:08:32.530 --> 00:08:37.210
and backward propagating waves.

00:08:37.210 --> 00:08:39.730
And this equation.

00:08:39.730 --> 00:08:41.679
Actually, it's a three
dimensional version.

00:08:41.679 --> 00:08:44.770
Not this one, but it's
three dimensional version.

00:08:44.770 --> 00:08:52.415
It has the name
Helmholtz wave equation.

00:08:56.690 --> 00:09:00.430
And because of Helmholtz,
it's a little bit difficult

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:02.560
to pronounce.

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:04.240
Actually, that's
not the real one.

00:09:04.240 --> 00:09:07.630
Anyway, it's a very commonly
encountered wave equation.

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:10.690
So typically we
simply omit Helmholtz,

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:12.710
and we say wave equation.

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:17.400
Now, why you might want to
distinguish this as opposed to

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:19.210
are there other wave equations?

00:09:19.210 --> 00:09:22.210
Yes, there is the
Schrodinger equation.

00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:26.410
There is the
Klein-Gordon equation.

00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:28.150
For those of you who
do fluid mechanics,

00:09:28.150 --> 00:09:32.110
there is a Korteweg-de Vries
equation, also known as KDV.

00:09:32.110 --> 00:09:34.960
There's a bunch of
different wave equations.

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:38.170
So we need some way
to discriminate.

00:09:38.170 --> 00:09:40.563
Nevertheless, the
other wave equations,

00:09:40.563 --> 00:09:41.980
they are referred
with their name.

00:09:41.980 --> 00:09:44.500
So when you want to refer
to Schrodinger's equation,

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:46.860
you say Schrodinger's equation.

00:09:46.860 --> 00:09:49.150
By convention, when
you say wave equation,

00:09:49.150 --> 00:09:51.610
you mean this one,
so the Helmholtz.

00:09:51.610 --> 00:09:53.950
OK.

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:56.930
So this is all very
nice, but it's actually

00:09:56.930 --> 00:09:58.460
down on your slide.

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:04.670
So there's no reason to agonize
over what I did over here.

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:10.480
What I would like to
remind you before I

00:10:10.480 --> 00:10:15.430
move on is for the
simple case of a--

00:10:15.430 --> 00:10:20.070
first of all, you
can imagine that this

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:22.530
is a very general
kind of solution.

00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:23.790
Because what is c?

00:10:23.790 --> 00:10:29.250
After all, I put up this
strange shape over here.

00:10:29.250 --> 00:10:30.670
I didn't say where it came from.

00:10:30.670 --> 00:10:33.930
So for that matter, if someone
gives you the wave question,

00:10:33.930 --> 00:10:36.300
how can you go
ahead and solve it?

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:40.080
Well, we're not going to do
this in great detail here.

00:10:40.080 --> 00:10:42.750
This is a little bit beside
the scope of the class.

00:10:42.750 --> 00:10:46.500
But generally, if you need to
solve a partial differential

00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:48.900
like this one, you need
additional information.

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:50.970
You need the initial conditions.

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:54.030
How did the wave start
at that time equals zero?

00:10:54.030 --> 00:10:55.860
And you also need the
boundary conditions.

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:59.130
So what happens to the
wave as it expands?

00:10:59.130 --> 00:11:01.200
Sometimes, the boundary
condition is at infinity.

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:02.760
Maybe the wave is not bounded.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:05.705
It can propagate
outwards all the way.

00:11:05.705 --> 00:11:07.080
And that's a good
example of what

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:13.600
happens if you are flying with a
helicopter on top of the ocean.

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:15.048
And you drop a--

00:11:15.048 --> 00:11:15.590
I don't know.

00:11:15.590 --> 00:11:18.240
You drop a stone into
the surface of the ocean.

00:11:18.240 --> 00:11:23.800
Then the wave that you generate,
the wave that you generate.

00:11:23.800 --> 00:11:26.360
To a good approximation, you
can use infinite boundary

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:27.110
conditions.

00:11:27.110 --> 00:11:31.990
Because the ocean is not quite
infinite, but very large.

00:11:31.990 --> 00:11:37.130
If you generate in a
wave in a small channel,

00:11:37.130 --> 00:11:41.060
then you might have to
include boundary conditions.

00:11:41.060 --> 00:11:42.770
Because the wave
will be confined

00:11:42.770 --> 00:11:44.450
by the walls of the channel.

00:11:44.450 --> 00:11:46.490
And we will see later
that this is actually

00:11:46.490 --> 00:11:48.320
quite commonly the case.

00:11:48.320 --> 00:11:50.040
In optics, we don't
call them channels.

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:52.220
We'll call them wave guides.

00:11:52.220 --> 00:11:56.810
But the boundary conditions can
actually significantly alter

00:11:56.810 --> 00:12:00.400
the shape of the wave.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:04.230
So what I did here is
just to give you an idea,

00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:08.070
I quote unquote, "solved."

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:09.660
Nothing interesting
happens here,

00:12:09.660 --> 00:12:12.720
but this is actually
solution of the wave

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:17.850
equation with a particular
initial condition, where

00:12:17.850 --> 00:12:19.560
time equals zero.

00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:23.250
The wave is a sinusoid.

00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:26.320
I said that this is my equation.

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:31.200
And I say that f
of z at t equals 0,

00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:39.750
equals some sinusoid amplitude
a, and wave number k.

00:12:39.750 --> 00:12:43.670
If that is the case,
then by inspection.

00:12:43.670 --> 00:12:45.000
I don't have to do anything.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:46.450
All very important.

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:50.290
And what I did not write
down, but it is implied,

00:12:50.290 --> 00:12:52.480
is that the boundary
conditions are free.

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:54.790
So this wave is
free to go as far

00:12:54.790 --> 00:13:00.350
as it pleases without
any special constraints.

00:13:00.350 --> 00:13:05.410
So if that is the case, then you
can write the solution almost

00:13:05.410 --> 00:13:06.460
by inspection.

00:13:06.460 --> 00:13:15.250
Half of z comma t equals
a cosine kz minus ct.

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:17.940
And you can see by inspection
here that because of the way

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:20.230
I wrote it, this
actually satisfies

00:13:20.230 --> 00:13:23.740
both the partial differential
equation, the wave equation,

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:25.250
and the boundary condition.

00:13:25.250 --> 00:13:30.560
So therefore, this is a proper
solution of the wave equation.

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:32.740
In fact, I only
wrote half of it.

00:13:32.740 --> 00:13:38.170
The wave, remember, it can go
forwards, and can go backwards.

00:13:38.170 --> 00:13:44.540
To cover both cases, I actually
write the solution this way.

00:13:44.540 --> 00:13:46.470
With the data that I
have here, actually, I

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:48.780
don't have enough to specify.

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:51.880
Or actually, in principle,
the wave can go both ways.

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:54.900
I would have to apply to give
you additional information

00:13:54.900 --> 00:13:58.920
to know which actually happened.

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:01.200
The other thing that
I wanted to point out,

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:05.190
which is not really difficult,
but it takes some getting used

00:14:05.190 --> 00:14:08.190
to, is the various
terms that appear

00:14:08.190 --> 00:14:11.740
inside this equation over here.

00:14:11.740 --> 00:14:14.850
So the term that we have
been very familiar with

00:14:14.850 --> 00:14:16.670
is the wavelength.

00:14:16.670 --> 00:14:19.620
There's another of those
crazy Greek symbols.

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:21.420
It's called lambda.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:24.960
And the wavelength is
related to the quantity

00:14:24.960 --> 00:14:32.430
that we have over here, as
2 pi over lambda equals k.

00:14:32.430 --> 00:14:34.980
So lambda is the
wavelength, as I said.

00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:39.280
K is known as the wave number.

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:42.960
So the relationship
that they have

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:45.510
is if you think of the
wavelength as a period--

00:14:45.510 --> 00:14:48.570
which it is, the period of
the wave in the space domain--

00:14:48.570 --> 00:14:55.620
then k would actually be
the angular frequency.

00:14:55.620 --> 00:14:59.550
But we'll call it wave number
to keep them separated.

00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:00.570
OK.

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:05.010
Equivalently, you can define
the actual angular frequency

00:15:05.010 --> 00:15:07.760
of the wave.

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:11.300
Usually this goes
by the symbol omega.

00:15:11.300 --> 00:15:13.550
And from this
equation over here,

00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:16.550
very simply you can see that
if you wanted to write it

00:15:16.550 --> 00:15:25.210
in the form a cosine kz
minus omega t, then clearly,

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:27.058
omega is the angular frequency.

00:15:27.058 --> 00:15:28.600
And when comparing
the two equations,

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:31.420
you can see that
omega equals kc.

00:15:31.420 --> 00:15:34.330
So the angular
frequency, then, is

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:45.060
related to the spatial
frequency, the wave number,

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:46.960
and the speed of the wave.

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:48.460
And of course, this
is nothing new.

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:54.407
We've seen this equation before,
but we saw it in disguise.

00:15:54.407 --> 00:15:55.990
And that's why I'm
going through this.

00:15:55.990 --> 00:15:58.780
Because all the symbols,
they can be played around

00:15:58.780 --> 00:16:00.220
with quite a bit.

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:03.040
So this equation, I can rewrite.

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:04.690
And the [INAUDIBLE]
is like this.

00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:07.360
So omega is the
angular frequency.

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:11.110
I also have the
plane, so to speak.

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:16.830
Frequency nu, which is
related as omega over 2 pi.

00:16:16.830 --> 00:16:20.910
One of them goes
[INAUDIBLE] radians.

00:16:20.910 --> 00:16:25.060
I'm sorry, it's measured
in full radians per second.

00:16:25.060 --> 00:16:26.040
This is omega.

00:16:26.040 --> 00:16:29.920
Nu is measured in hertz,
simply inverse seconds.

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:32.600
Bless you.

00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:34.350
So I can substitute
in this equation.

00:16:34.350 --> 00:16:37.510
Omega is 2 pi times nu.

00:16:37.510 --> 00:16:41.820
