00:34:10.929 --> 00:34:13.835
I'm introducing phasors now.

00:34:13.835 --> 00:34:16.210
And the reason, of course,
that we're introducing phasors

00:34:16.210 --> 00:34:19.690
is because we don't
want to have to remember

00:34:19.690 --> 00:34:22.810
complicated identities
like this one.

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:29.159
By the way, another
point that I would

00:34:29.159 --> 00:34:32.429
like to bring up before
I move on to phasors

00:34:32.429 --> 00:34:37.110
is that the wave
that I'm showing here

00:34:37.110 --> 00:34:41.199
is actually very different
than the traveling wave that

00:34:41.199 --> 00:34:42.822
led us to the wave equation.

00:34:42.822 --> 00:34:43.780
You'll agree with that.

00:34:43.780 --> 00:34:46.360
That looks very
different, both in the way

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:50.650
it behaves with time
and space, and the way

00:34:50.650 --> 00:34:52.639
it looks like an equation.

00:34:52.639 --> 00:34:56.600
Yet, it still originated
from the same wave equation.

00:34:56.600 --> 00:35:00.190
So this is actually the power of
partial differential equations

00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:01.870
and superposition.

00:35:01.870 --> 00:35:05.770
That I took two solutions
with my partial differential

00:35:05.770 --> 00:35:08.005
equation that were not
particularly interesting,

00:35:08.005 --> 00:35:10.560
I superimposed them, and
then all of a sudden,

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:13.390
I created another
solution, which

00:35:13.390 --> 00:35:16.180
is still a very valid wave,
but we have totally different.

00:35:16.180 --> 00:35:18.040
It is a stationary wave.

00:35:18.040 --> 00:35:21.230
It has this oscillation,
and so on and so forth.

00:35:21.230 --> 00:35:25.150
So that is why we bother to
write this partial differential

00:35:25.150 --> 00:35:28.840
equation, because it
allows us to generate

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:33.117
a much richer set
of waves that are,

00:35:33.117 --> 00:35:34.700
of course, very
important in practice.

00:35:34.700 --> 00:35:38.382
Standing waves
happen all the time.

00:35:38.382 --> 00:35:39.715
OK, so now, let's go to phasors.

00:35:44.970 --> 00:35:49.750
OK, so just like before,
I wrote two waves

00:35:49.750 --> 00:35:52.667
that were propagating
in opposite directions.

00:35:52.667 --> 00:35:54.250
Now, what I'm going
to do is I'm going

00:35:54.250 --> 00:35:59.110
to write two waves that are
phase shifted by pi over two.

00:35:59.110 --> 00:36:05.465
So one of them is cosine
kz minus omega t plus phi.

00:36:09.140 --> 00:36:10.920
And the other is
phase shifted by pi

00:36:10.920 --> 00:36:13.550
over 2, which means instead
of a cosine, it is a sine.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:26.570
OK, both are valid solutions
to the wave equation

00:36:26.570 --> 00:36:28.410
with different
initial conditions,

00:36:28.410 --> 00:36:29.830
but that doesn't bother us.

00:36:29.830 --> 00:36:32.300
They're still valid solutions.

00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:34.955
Therefore, their superposition
is also a solution.

00:36:37.820 --> 00:36:40.610
And I said before that when
you do a linear superposition,

00:36:40.610 --> 00:36:45.440
you can also multiply the
waves by arbitrary constants.

00:36:45.440 --> 00:36:48.210
I said this a little
bit fast, but I hope

00:36:48.210 --> 00:36:50.670
that remember that I said it.

00:36:50.670 --> 00:36:53.250
In fact, in this class, we
have evidence of what I said

00:36:53.250 --> 00:36:54.320
and what I did not say.

00:36:54.320 --> 00:36:58.590
Then go back to the video and
see if I said it, and I did.

00:36:58.590 --> 00:37:00.820
So I will pick a very
particular constant,

00:37:00.820 --> 00:37:03.890
which may sound like a crazy
choice, but I will pick it.

00:37:03.890 --> 00:37:07.690
And that is the imaginary
constant, i, also known

00:37:07.690 --> 00:37:12.900
as one of the two
square root of minus 1.

00:37:12.900 --> 00:37:15.360
OK, what is this now?

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:17.580
So the first confession
that I will make

00:37:17.580 --> 00:37:20.210
is that it is not
physical anymore.

00:37:20.210 --> 00:37:23.280
There's no such thing
as a complex wave.

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:25.290
The waves that we see
around us are real.

00:37:25.290 --> 00:37:28.290
They can be measured
by instruments,

00:37:28.290 --> 00:37:32.030
such as oscilloscope, scanners,
I don't know what else.

00:37:32.030 --> 00:37:34.110
They're real.

00:37:34.110 --> 00:37:37.410
As far as I know, nobody has
ever measured anything complex.

00:37:37.410 --> 00:37:41.190
However, what I'm doing here
is mathematically correct,

00:37:41.190 --> 00:37:43.560
even if it has no
physical meaning.

00:37:43.560 --> 00:37:47.040
And as it turns out, it
provides a huge mathematical

00:37:47.040 --> 00:37:48.090
convenience.

00:37:48.090 --> 00:37:52.380
So I'm justified in doing it
as long as I remember what

00:37:52.380 --> 00:37:54.450
is the physics that is behind.

00:37:54.450 --> 00:37:56.040
And the physics
that is behind it

00:37:56.040 --> 00:37:59.240
is that every time I
see a wave like this,

00:37:59.240 --> 00:38:02.490
I have to remember that
the physical quantity is

00:38:02.490 --> 00:38:04.720
the real part.

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:06.700
So the physical wave--

00:38:06.700 --> 00:38:10.480
the one that I can
actually measure, observe,

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:14.170
generate with natural means--

00:38:14.170 --> 00:38:17.550
is the real part.

00:38:17.550 --> 00:38:19.890
The imaginary part is
something that I added

00:38:19.890 --> 00:38:23.190
for mathematical convenience.

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:26.520
And it isn't reality because
I forget whose formula.

00:38:26.520 --> 00:38:28.840
It is called the De Moivre.

00:38:34.010 --> 00:38:35.760
Anyway, one of those.

00:38:40.500 --> 00:38:41.000
D-E?

00:38:43.930 --> 00:38:44.620
Moivre, yeah.

00:38:44.620 --> 00:38:45.100
AUDIENCE: De Moivre.

00:38:45.100 --> 00:38:46.642
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
De Moivre, yeah.

00:38:46.642 --> 00:38:48.520
OK, I got it right.

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:50.430
So De Moivre, then, if
I remember correctly,

00:38:50.430 --> 00:38:51.430
that's how you spell it.

00:38:54.520 --> 00:39:03.180
De Moivre says that this thing
here is a complex exponential.

00:39:10.180 --> 00:39:14.060
So that's very nice
because for example,

00:39:14.060 --> 00:39:18.660
if you have to multiply two
cosines, it's a big pain.

00:39:18.660 --> 00:39:21.660
You have to remember the trig
to multiply two exponential.

00:39:21.660 --> 00:39:22.340
It is trivial.

00:39:22.340 --> 00:39:26.850
You just add their phases,
I mean, their exponents.

00:39:26.850 --> 00:39:31.960
So a lot of inconveniences
to be to be expected.

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:35.940
So this representation, it
comes with different names,

00:39:35.940 --> 00:39:39.090
which are sometimes
used confusingly

00:39:39.090 --> 00:39:41.460
in an interchangeable way.

00:39:41.460 --> 00:39:45.240
So some people call
this a phasor notation.

00:39:45.240 --> 00:39:47.760
I prefer to call this the
complex representation

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:49.820
of the wave.

00:39:49.820 --> 00:39:53.170
It becomes a phasor
when we drop--

00:39:53.170 --> 00:39:55.060
I'm going to do
something nasty here.

00:39:55.060 --> 00:39:57.400
OK, remember that I can
write this as a project.

00:39:57.400 --> 00:40:03.540
So I can write this as e to the
ikz, e to the minus i omega t,

00:40:03.540 --> 00:40:06.020
e to the i phi.

00:40:06.020 --> 00:40:07.840
OK.

00:40:07.840 --> 00:40:12.660
If you recall during the
beginnings of the class,

00:40:12.660 --> 00:40:18.820
we saw that the wavelength
in the middle changes.

00:40:18.820 --> 00:40:22.896
But there is a property of
the wave that does not change.

00:40:22.896 --> 00:40:24.550
And that property,
if you recall,

00:40:24.550 --> 00:40:28.200
is the temporal
frequency, omega, or nu,

00:40:28.200 --> 00:40:29.580
which are related by two pi.

00:40:32.540 --> 00:40:34.280
That is true in linear media.

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:36.500
Of course, there is
a class of optics

00:40:36.500 --> 00:40:39.390
called non-linear, where
actually, the frequency can

00:40:39.390 --> 00:40:39.890
change.

00:40:39.890 --> 00:40:42.890
It can double, or it can
half, or [INAUDIBLE] of things

00:40:42.890 --> 00:40:43.655
can happen to it.

00:40:43.655 --> 00:40:46.280
But in this class, we don't deal
with these complicated things.

00:40:46.280 --> 00:40:48.620
We just deal with linear optics.

00:40:48.620 --> 00:40:51.260
So in linear optics,
the temporal frequency

00:40:51.260 --> 00:40:53.730
of the light, no matter
what happens to the light.

00:40:53.730 --> 00:40:57.050
If it goes through
glass and reflects,

00:40:57.050 --> 00:40:58.220
and all kinds of things.

00:40:58.220 --> 00:41:00.690
The temporal frequency
remains the same.

00:41:00.690 --> 00:41:04.970
So when we deal with optical
waves of a single frequency--

00:41:04.970 --> 00:41:10.340
that is the quality's fixed
and the medium is linear--

00:41:10.340 --> 00:41:12.860
then this term is
actually superfluous.

00:41:12.860 --> 00:41:16.880
We don't have to remind
ourselves that the light goes

00:41:16.880 --> 00:41:18.920
like e to the minus omega t.

00:41:18.920 --> 00:41:21.410
It does, but we don't
have to write it.

00:41:21.410 --> 00:41:25.010
Because if we keep writing
it, it clutters our equations.

00:41:25.010 --> 00:41:26.510
So we simply drop it.

00:41:29.750 --> 00:41:30.590
We drop it.

00:41:30.590 --> 00:41:31.770
Very important to remember.

00:41:31.770 --> 00:41:33.830
We are allowed to
drop it if we know

00:41:33.830 --> 00:41:37.340
that we have a single color in
our system, a single frequency.

00:41:37.340 --> 00:41:38.780
If there is multiple
frequencies,

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:40.040
we can not do that anymore.

00:41:40.040 --> 00:41:43.790
Because then these frequencies
have to adapt in a certain way,

00:41:43.790 --> 00:41:47.000
and you have to keep track
of their additive phases.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.880
So we can only drop
this term if we--

00:41:49.880 --> 00:41:50.570
two conditions.

00:41:50.570 --> 00:41:52.820
If we know that we
have a linear medium,

00:41:52.820 --> 00:41:57.530
and a single frequency light
propagating in that medium.

00:41:57.530 --> 00:42:03.090
So in my terminology, at
least, after we drop this term,

00:42:03.090 --> 00:42:04.740
then it becomes a phasor.

00:42:04.740 --> 00:42:05.750
So what is left?

00:42:05.750 --> 00:42:08.830
e to the ikz plus 5.

00:42:08.830 --> 00:42:10.450
That, I call a phasor.

00:42:10.450 --> 00:42:12.040
And you notice
what happened there

00:42:12.040 --> 00:42:16.990
is I only left the spatial
dependency of the wave

00:42:16.990 --> 00:42:18.800
plus the phase delay.

00:42:18.800 --> 00:42:21.220
The temporal variation is--

00:42:21.220 --> 00:42:21.760
it's hidden.

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:22.450
It is not gone.

00:42:22.450 --> 00:42:25.710
It is just hidden.

00:42:25.710 --> 00:42:29.440
OK, now let's see
this in action.

00:42:29.440 --> 00:42:32.860
So what I'm going to do is I'm
going to rederive the standing

00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:34.750
wave, but using the phasor.

00:42:34.750 --> 00:42:36.970
So you can see how nice
and simple it comes out,

00:42:36.970 --> 00:42:39.260
and we don't have
to agonize over it.

00:42:39.260 --> 00:42:43.380
But before I do it, I actually
have to solve a little problem.

00:42:43.380 --> 00:42:45.970
And the problem is that I
did this very nice derivation

00:42:45.970 --> 00:42:49.630
for the phasor of the
forward propagating wave.

00:42:49.630 --> 00:42:54.940
What about the phasor for the
backward propagating wave?

00:42:54.940 --> 00:42:59.530
The backward propagating wave
will be something of this sort.

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:01.110
So this will always
forward, right?

00:43:07.260 --> 00:43:08.788
Let me write the backward.

00:43:08.788 --> 00:43:10.830
I think I have enough
space here, so I can do it.

00:43:16.670 --> 00:43:19.240
OK, so the backward
would be something

00:43:19.240 --> 00:43:26.770
of the sort of the form
of cosine, az plus omega t

00:43:26.770 --> 00:43:29.303
plus phi.

00:43:29.303 --> 00:43:30.470
And it is very inconvenient.

00:43:30.470 --> 00:43:32.960
Because the way I
got the phasor is

00:43:32.960 --> 00:43:38.980
I got rid of a term of the
forward to the minus omega t.

00:43:38.980 --> 00:43:44.200
If I add the
imaginary part here,

00:43:44.200 --> 00:43:49.000
I don't have a term e to the
minus omega t, so I'm stuck.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:51.850
But I can do some
mathematical trickery.

00:43:51.850 --> 00:43:55.138
Now, this is pure
trickery, but it works.

00:43:55.138 --> 00:43:56.430
The trick, it is the following.

00:43:56.430 --> 00:44:00.270
We know that the cosine
is an even function.

00:44:00.270 --> 00:44:04.360
So this is actually identical.

00:44:04.360 --> 00:44:06.200
I can replace it,
in other words,

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:08.080
with the cosine of
the negative element.

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:15.440
No harm done.

00:44:15.440 --> 00:44:17.210
It is still a backward
propagating wave.

00:44:17.210 --> 00:44:18.140
Nothing has changed.

00:44:18.140 --> 00:44:20.290
It is the same equation.

00:44:20.290 --> 00:44:24.540
Now, according to my good
principle here, I add.

00:44:31.360 --> 00:44:34.310
That is not the same as before.

00:44:34.310 --> 00:44:37.430
Because the sign
is an odd function.

00:44:37.430 --> 00:44:39.180
But this is a
non-physical term, anyway.

00:44:39.180 --> 00:44:41.222
I just put it there for
mathematical convenience,

00:44:41.222 --> 00:44:42.910
so I don't particularly care.

00:44:42.910 --> 00:44:45.320
I'm very happy,
because the real part

00:44:45.320 --> 00:44:48.250
is the same as I started with.

00:44:48.250 --> 00:44:50.870
What the imaginary part does--

00:44:50.870 --> 00:44:52.660
as long as it's
mathematically convenient,

00:44:52.660 --> 00:44:54.360
I couldn't care less.

00:44:54.360 --> 00:44:56.780
OK, so that gives me the
license to write this.

00:44:56.780 --> 00:45:02.890
Now, this, of course,
equals e to the minus

00:45:02.890 --> 00:45:09.440
ikz minus omega t minus phi.

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:11.780
Now very happy, because
I did get a term e

00:45:11.780 --> 00:45:16.700
to the minus i omega t in the
phase of this exponential.

00:45:16.700 --> 00:45:19.490
And therefore, I can drop
it to produce my phasor.

00:45:19.490 --> 00:45:21.400
So the last one, then,
is that the phasor

00:45:21.400 --> 00:45:29.960
for the backward wave is e
to the minus ikz minus i phi.

00:45:29.960 --> 00:45:32.720
In other words, if I give you
a forward propagating wave,

00:45:32.720 --> 00:45:34.475
and you compute its phasor.

00:45:34.475 --> 00:45:37.100
And then I asked you, well, what
is the phasor for the backward

00:45:37.100 --> 00:45:38.630
propagating wave?

00:45:38.630 --> 00:45:41.000
Well, all you do is you flip
the sign and the exponent.

00:45:48.030 --> 00:45:48.730
Whoa.

00:45:48.730 --> 00:45:49.870
Where did this come from?

00:45:49.870 --> 00:45:55.790
I think this is an old paper
from some previous lecture.

00:45:55.790 --> 00:45:57.820
But anyway, ignore this.

00:46:01.010 --> 00:46:04.750
I have to remember to ask
for a new paper next time.

00:46:04.750 --> 00:46:06.330
OK, so what I will do now.

00:46:06.330 --> 00:46:08.470
Let me reproduce
the standing wave.

00:46:08.470 --> 00:46:12.930
So the standing wave is
using the phasors now.

00:46:12.930 --> 00:46:17.460
It's e to the ikz plus phi.

00:46:17.460 --> 00:46:24.630
That is the forward wave, plus
e to the minus ikz minus i phi.

00:46:28.680 --> 00:46:32.215
That is the backward wave.

00:46:32.215 --> 00:46:33.090
Can I deal with that?

00:46:33.090 --> 00:46:33.923
Well, yes, actually.

00:46:33.923 --> 00:46:36.350
Because, again, De Moivre
says that if you add

00:46:36.350 --> 00:46:38.240
two exponential of this form--

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:42.660
notice they have the same
